wcg_strategy: I had no strategy per se, but once I thought of an object, such as a mountain, I naturally started thinking about other objects that would be in the same picture, such as trees and moss and rocks. guess_experiment: I think this experiment is trying to measure how much reading a story influences how our brain creates chains of words.
wcg_diff_general: The big difference I felt was that I seemed to be more highly focused on images from out of doors, and in particular I was thinking of the mountainous environment of the story, the spooky green pickup which followed the heroine, and the road on which they drove. The story definitely influenced my second round of the word chain game as images from it were fresh in my mind. This might be because I am personally very familiar with the Naches river and the highway which goes alongside it, since I have gone fishing and gold panning there many times!
volition_explanation: I am very familiar with the Naches river area, the Little Naches, Bumping Lake, Gold Hill, and the highway which follows the river. I have been there many times. I suspect this is why the story had a huge visual impact on me. The images of the area came to my mind automatically, but I lingered over them deliberately as I remembered the story. Part of the lingering was sheer nostalgia for the many fun times I had in the area in my youth. So aspects of this story came to my mind both unintentionally, and intentionally.
wcg_diff_explanation: As I have said, I am very familiar with the geographical area of this story in real life, so I had a very different feeling when completing the second word chain game. It was a combination of nostalgia and a kind of headiness, and also some low level anxiety when thinking about the highway and the man in the truck following Claire.
open_box: This was a very well organized study and the story was very engaging.  Also, I was very surprised to encounter a story which featured the Naches River and surrounding area, where I have spent many fun camping trips.
